            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> Sounds a bit like a niche use-case - but maybe you can elaborate on the scenario you have?\n\nSure thing. Just like in the [reddit thread above](https://www.reddit.com/r/neovim/comments/15h6f4o/lsp_is_started_even_though_i_change_the_filetype/). I've got a file whose detected FileType changes while neovim is opening it. Here's an example:\n\n`myscript`:\n\n```python\n#!/usr/bin/env nix-shell\n#!nix-shell -i python3 -p python3\n\n# vi: ft=python\n\nprint(\"Hello, world!\")\n```\n\nWhen opening this file, neovim first detects that this filetype is `nix`, and then later the filetype changes to `python`. Proof:\n\n`init.lua`:\n\n```lua\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd({\"FileType\"}, {\n  callback = function(ev)\n    print(string.format('FileType is now %s', ev.match))\n  end\n})\n```\n\nAnd then open `myscript`:\n\n```console\n$ nvim -u init.lua myscript\n```\n\nAnd then run `:messages` and see:\n\n```\nFileType is now nix\nFileType is now python\n```\n\nIf you've got LSPs configured for both nix and python, you'll end up with both of them running for this one file. I'd believe the more sane behavior would be for neovim to stop the `nix` LSP when the filetype changes from `nix` to `python`.",
